@database pstops.guide

@node main "pstops.guide"

PSUtils Release 1 Patchlevel 16


NAME

pstops - shuffle pages in a PostScript file


SYNOPSIS

@{b}pstops@{ub} [@{b}-q@{ub}] [@{b}-b@{ub}] [@{b}-w@{ub}@{i}width@{ui}] [@{b}-h@{ub}@{i}height@{ui}] [@{b}-p@{ub}@{i}paper@{ui}] [@{b}-d@{ub}@{i}width@{ui}]
       @{i}pagespecs@{ui} [@{i}infile@{ui} [@{i}outfile@{ui}] ]


DESCRIPTION

@{i}Pstops@{ui} rearranges pages from a PostScript document, creating
a new PostScript file.  The input PostScript file should follow the
Adobe Document Structuring Conventions.  @{i}Pstops@{ui} can be used
to perform a large number of arbitrary re-arrangements of Documents,
including arranging for printing 2-up, 4-up, booklets, reversing,
selecting front or back sides of documents, scaling, etc.

@{i}pagespecs@{ui} follow the syntax:

@{i}pagespecs@{ui} = [@{i}modulo@{ui}:]@{i}specs@{ui}

@{i}specs@{ui} = @{i}spec@{ui}[+@{i}specs@{ui}][,@{i}specs@{ui}]

@{i}spec@{ui} = [-]@{i}pageno@{ui}[L][R][U][@@{i}scale@{ui}][(@{i}xoff@{ui},@{i}yoff@{ui})]

@{i}modulo@{ui} is the number of pages in each block. The value of @{i}modulo@{ui}
should be greater than 0; the default value is 1.  @{i}specs@{ui} are
the page specifications for the pages in each block. The value of the
@{i}pageno@{ui} in each @{i}spec@{ui} should be between 0 (for the first
page in the block) and @{i}modulo@{ui}-1 (for the last page in each
block) inclusive.

The optional dimensions @{i}xoff@{ui} and @{i}yoff@{ui} shift the page by
the specified amount.  @{i}xoff@{ui} and @{i}yoff@{ui} are in PostScript's
points, but may be followed by the units @{b}"cm"@{ub} or @{b}"in"@{ub} to
convert to centimetres or inches, or the flag @{b}"w"@{ub} or @{b}"h"@{ub}
to specify as a multiple of the width or height.

The optional parameters @{b}L@{ub}, @{b}R@{ub}, and @{b}U@{ub} rotate the
page left, right, or upside-down.

The optional @{i}scale@{ui} parameter scales the page by the fraction
specified.  If the optional minus sign is specified, the page is relative
to the end of the document, instead of the start.

If page @{i}spec@{ui} are separated by @{b}+@{ub} the pages will be merged
into one page; if they are separated by @{b},@{ub} they will be on separate
pages.  If there is only one page specification, with @{i}pageno@{ui} zero,
the @{i}pageno@{ui} may be omitted.

The shift, rotation, and scaling are performed in that order regardless
of which order they appear on the command line.

The @{b}-w@{ub} option gives the width which is used by the @{b}"w"@{ub}
dimension specifier, and the @{b}-h@{ub} option gives the height which
is used by the @{b}"h"@{ub} dimension specifier. These dimensions are
also used (after scaling) to set the clipping path for each page.

The @{b}-p@{ub} option can be used as an alternative, to set the paper size
to @{b}a3, a4, a5, b5, letter, legal, tabloid, statement, executive,
@{b}folio, quarto@{ub} or @{b}10x14@{ub}.

The default paper size is @{b}a4.@{ub}  @{i}(If you wish to re-compile the source,
you may #def PAPER - DF).@{ui}

The @{b}-b@{ub} option prevents any @{b}bind@{ub} operators in the PostScript
prolog from binding. This may be needed in cases where complex multi-page
re-arrangements are being done.

The @{b}-d@{ub} option draws a line around the border of each page, of
the specified width.  If the @{i}lwidth@{ui} parameter is omitted, a
default linewidth of 1 point is assumed. The linewidth is relative
to the original page dimensions, @{i}i.e.@{ui} it is scaled up or down
with the rest of the page.

@{i}Pstops@{ui} normally prints the page numbers of the pages re-arranged;
the @{b}-q@{ub} option suppresses this.


EXAMPLES

This section contains some sample re-arrangements. To put two pages on one
sheet (of A4 paper), the pagespec to use is:

2:0L@.7(21cm,0)+1L@.7(21cm,14.85cm)

@{i}(DF - This, and other examples, are for A4 paper)@{ui}

To select all of the odd pages in reverse order, use:

2:-0

To re-arrange pages for printing 2-up booklets, use

4:-3L@.7(21cm,0)+0L@.7(21cm,14.85cm)

for the front sides, and

4:1L@.7(21cm,0)+-2L@.7(21cm,14.85cm)

for the reverse sides (or join them with a comma for duplex printing).


